\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  Direct application of Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_finrank_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_X4} to $F := \Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$, via the dot-notation method-call form $S.\mathtt{finrank\_HModule\_eq\_HModule}'\_X_4\,k\,\_\,n$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-036 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Module.Finite transport via the corner-bridge (iter-037)}

The iter-035 corner-bridge $\AffineCoverMVSquare.\HModulePrime\_X_4\_\mathtt{linearEquiv}$ is a $k$-linear isomorphism, so the property \emph{``the underlying $k$-module is finite''} transports across it: if $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X_4$ is finite over $k$, so is $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$. This is the algebraic counterpart of the iter-036 finrank corollary — the same one-step transport, but now landing on $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}$ rather than $\mathrm{finrank}$. It is the precise downstream hypothesis $\mathtt{smoothOfRelativeDimension\_genus}$ (Jacobian.lean) will eventually consume. Step 4 (the actual proof that $\HModulePrime\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n\,X_4$ is finite — typically via affine-vanishing and the finiteness of $H^0(\Spec A, \mathcal O_{\Spec A}) = A$ for $A$ a finitely generated $k$-algebra) is iter-038+.

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[$\HModule$-finiteness via $X_4$ corner, abstract sheaf form, iter-037]
  \label{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.AffineCoverMVSquare.module_finite_HModule_of_HModule'_X₄}
  \uses{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_HModule_prime_X4_linearEquiv, def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  Let $k$ be a field, $X : \Scheme$, $S : X.\AffineCoverMVSquare$, $F : \Sheaf\,(\mathtt{Opens.grothendieckTopology}\,X.\mathtt{toTopCat})\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, $n \in \mathbb{N}$, and assume $\HasExt_u$ and $\HasExt_{u+1}$ for the same sheaf category. If $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(S.\mathtt{toMayerVietorisSquare}.\mathtt{toSquare}.X_4)$ is a finite $k$-module, then so is $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  Apply Mathlib's $\Module.\mathtt{Finite.equiv}$ ($\mathtt{Mathlib/RingTheory/Finiteness/Basic.lean}$, signature $(e : M \equiv_R N) [\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,R\,M] : \Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,R\,N$) to the iter-035 corner-bridge $\AffineCoverMVSquare.\HModulePrime\_X_4\_\mathtt{linearEquiv}$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_HModule_prime_X4_linearEquiv}), which carries $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X_4 \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ in exactly the orientation $\Module.\mathtt{Finite.equiv}$ wants (LHS hypothesis, RHS conclusion). Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-037 pass) confirms the one-liner $\Module.\mathtt{Finite.equiv}\,(S.\HModulePrime\_X_4\_\mathtt{linearEquiv}\,k\,F\,n)$ typechecks end-to-end with kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[$\HModule$-finiteness via $X_4$ corner, curve form, iter-037]
  \label{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.AffineCoverMVSquare.module_finite_HModule_of_HModule'_X₄_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$, $S : C.\mathtt{left}.\AffineCoverMVSquare$, $n \in \mathbb{N}$, and assume $\HasExt_u$ and $\HasExt_{u+1}$ for $\Sheaf\,(\mathtt{Opens.grothendieckTopology}\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat})\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$. If $\HModulePrime\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n\,(S.\mathtt{toMayerVietorisSquare}.\mathtt{toSquare}.X_4)$ is a finite $k$-module, then so is $\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  Direct application of Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4} to $F := \Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$, via the dot-notation method-call form $S.\mathtt{module\_finite\_HModule\_of\_HModule}'\_X_4\,k\,\_\,n$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-037 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Top-supremum HModule transport (iter-049)}

The iter-048 carrier predicate $\Scheme.\IsCechAcyclicCover$ (\texttt{Cohomology/StructureSheafModuleK.lean}) lifts via its consumer $\mathtt{subsingleton\_HModule}'\_\mathtt{supr\_of\_isCechAcyclicCover}$ to a $\Subsingleton$ on $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i)$. This lives at universe $u$. The iter-053+ genus carrier $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$, on the other hand, lives at universe $u+1$, since $\genus\,C = \mathrm{finrank}_k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$ (iter-011) is built on the universe-$u+1$ form $\HModule = \Ext_{u+1}\,((\mathtt{constantSheaf})\,(\ModuleCat.\mathtt{of}\,k\,k))\,F\,n$. The iter-034 universal bridge $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$ already crosses this gap. Iter-049 chains the two: under the cover-totality hypothesis $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$, the iter-048 conclusion $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup\mathcal U))$ rewrites to $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,\top)$, which iter-034's bridge (composed with $\mathtt{Equiv.subsingleton}$) transports to $\Subsingleton\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$. This is the universe-$u+1$ form of iter-048's vanishing, ready to be consumed by iter-053+.

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Top-supremum HModule transport, abstract sheaf form, iter-049]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover, def:Scheme_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_linearEquiv, def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$, and $F$ a sheaf of $\ModuleCat\,k$ on $\mathtt{Opens}\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$. Assume both $\HasExt_u$ and $\HasExt_{u+1}$ on the same sheaf category. Let $\mathcal U : \iota \to \Opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$ be a cover with $[\Scheme.\IsCechAcyclicCover\,F\,\mathcal U]$ and $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$. Given an explicit comparison iso $\mathtt{compIso} : \forall n,\ \cechCohomology\,C\,F\,\mathcal U\,n \equiv_{k} \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i)$ and $n \geq 1$, the underlying type of $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ is a subsingleton.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}

\leanok
  Apply the iter-048 consumer $\mathtt{subsingleton\_HModule}'\_\mathtt{supr\_of\_isCechAcyclicCover}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_prime_supr_of_isCechAcyclicCover}) to the iter-048 class $[\IsCechAcyclicCover\,F\,\mathcal U]$ + $\mathtt{compIso}$ + $n$ + the positivity $n \geq 1$, obtaining $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i))$. Rewrite via $h : \bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$ (using $h \rhd \mathtt{this}$) to $\Subsingleton\,(\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,\top)$. Apply the iter-034 universal bridge $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{eq}\_\HModule\_\mathtt{linearEquiv}\,k\,F\,n\,(\mathtt{Preorder.isTerminalTop}\,\_)$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_linearEquiv}) — which lifts the lattice's $\top$ to a categorical $\IsTerminal\,\top$ via Mathlib's $\Preorder.\mathtt{isTerminalTop}$ — to obtain a $\LinearEquiv$ between $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,\top$ and $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$. Pass through $.\mathtt{symm.toEquiv.subsingleton}$ to transport the $\Subsingleton$ structure across the iso, landing on $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-049 pass) confirms the body $\mathtt{by\ haveI\ ::\ haveI\ ::\ exact\ \ldots}$ typechecks end-to-end with kernel-only axioms $[\propext, \mathtt{Classical.choice}, \mathtt{Quot.sound}]$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Top-supremum HModule transport, curve form, iter-049]
  \label{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top_curve}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top_curve}
  \uses{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Let $k$ be a field and $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$. Assume both $\HasExt_u$ and $\HasExt_{u+1}$. Let $\mathcal U : \iota \to \Opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$ with $[\Scheme.\IsCechAcyclicCover\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,\mathcal U]$ and $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = \top$. Given $\mathtt{compIso}$ at $F := \Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ and $n \geq 1$, the underlying type of $\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n$ is a subsingleton.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}

\leanok
  Direct application of Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top} to $F := \Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ via the named-argument syntax $\mathtt{subsingleton\_HModule\_of\_isCechAcyclicCover\_top}\,(\mathcal U := \mathcal U)\,h\,\mathtt{compIso}\,n\,h_n$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-049 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}

The iter-029 lemmas materialise Step 1 (the abstract LES) and Step 2 (the corner-identification simp lemmas) of the iter-028 Serre-finiteness sketch (Section~\ref{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare}); iter-030 materialised Step 2.5 (the toModuleKSheaf specialisation, a routine binding so downstream code paths can reference the LES on the structure sheaf of a curve directly); iter-031 materialised the \emph{source-object} half of Step 3 (the cover-totality identification at the sheaf level); iter-032 materialised the \emph{Ext-transport} half of Step 3 at universe $u+1$ (landing on $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$); iter-033 materialised the parallel \emph{Ext-transport} at universe $u$ (landing on $\Ext_u\,X_2\,F\,n$); iter-034 closed Step 3 by appending the Mathlib gap-fill $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUnivLinearEquiv}$ (universe-bump $\LinearEquiv$ upgrade of Mathlib's bare $\Equiv$ $\Ext.\mathtt{chgUniv}$) and composing iter-033 with it to produce the full bridge $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$; iter-035 closed Step 3.5 (the \emph{corner-bridge}) by specialising the iter-034 universal bridge to the $X_4$ corner of an $\AffineCoverMVSquare$ — both an abstract sheaf form (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_HModule_prime_X4_linearEquiv}) and a curve specialisation (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_HModule_prime_X4_linearEquiv_curve}); iter-036 appended the immediate \emph{finrank corollary} (Theorems~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_finrank_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_X4} and~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_finrank_HModule_eq_HModule_prime_X4_curve}) — landing the genus carrier $\mathrm{finrank}_k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$ on the explicit corner $X_4$ via $\LinearEquiv.\mathtt{finrank\_eq}$; iter-037 appends the parallel \emph{$\Module.\mathtt{Finite}$ transport companion} (Theorems~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4} and~\ref{thm:Scheme_AffineCoverMVSquare_module_finite_HModule_of_HModule_prime_X4_curve}) — the algebraic counterpart of iter-036, transporting finiteness rather than finrank across the corner-bridge, via Mathlib's $\Module.\mathtt{Finite.equiv}$. Iter-038 → iter-046 build the H⁰ Module.Finite ladder (curve specialisations + carrier predicates + Stein input + global-sections evaluation iso + producer chain end-to-end for $\IsHModuleHomFinite\,k\,C\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$); iter-047 lays foundational parameterised Čech infrastructure; iter-048 appends the Čech-side acyclicity carrier predicate and abstract consumer; iter-049 (this iteration) appends the top-supremum HModule transport (Theorems~\ref{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top} and~\ref{thm:Scheme_subsingleton_HModule_of_isCechAcyclicCover_top_curve}) — the universe $u \to u+1$ bridge that lets iter-053+ ultimately consume iter-048's $\Subsingleton$ on $\HModulePrime$ at the lattice supremum to derive the genus carrier $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1)$ at universe $u+1$. The remaining work — Step 4 (the substantive Čech-vs-derived comparison theorem; iter-050+ multi-iteration; Mathlib has $\mathtt{cechComplexFunctor}$ but no comparison theorem) and Step 5 (basic-open cover acyclicity producers; iter-051+ computational; Koszul-like alternating-sum complex on localisations is exact) and Step 6 (assembling the genus carrier from the LES + iter-035/049 transport + Step 4/5 affine input) is iter-050+.

